CPU Utilization: Tracking the processor workload generated by the database engine to prevent performance bottlenecks caused by heavy computations or poorly indexed queries.

Memory Usage: Monitoring how much RAM the database consumes to ensure data pages stay cached in memory rather than forcing slow reads from physical disks.

Disk Space: Auditing the remaining storage capacity on filesystems hosting data and log files to prevent catastrophic database shutdowns when disks fill up.

Database Growth: Measuring the expansion rate of database files over time to accurately forecast future storage acquisition needs and manage file auto-growth settings.

Long-Running Queries: Isolating SQL statements that exceed expected execution durations so they can be tuned before they drain server resources or time out.

Blocking and Deadlocks: Monitoring connection lock states to identify sessions stalling other users or causing the engine to kill conflicting transactions


